Comparison of ANOVA with linear models

Two samples with the same variance

Letâs generate two sample groups, ctrl and trt, by taking random samples from normally distributed data.

# Select 5 random numbers from distribution where *mean*=0 and *sd*=1
ctrl=rnorm(5)

# Select 5 random numbers from distribution where *mean*=5 and *sd*= 1
trt = rnorm(5, mean=5)

# Combine both samples into one vector
data = c(ctrl,trt)

# Define how the data should be grouped
expgroups = factor(rep(c("ctrl", "trt"), each=5))

# Use a boxplot to show the distributions
boxplot(data ~ expgroups)

Perform ANOVA

The model is written such that the dependent variable (data) is explained by the independent variable (expgroups).

NOTE: Two ways to perform an ANOVA analysis are to use either the aov() function or the lm() function.

ANOVA Method 1: aov()

NOTE: There are two equivalent ways look at a summary of an ANOVA using the aov() command, summary(aov(data~expgroups)) and summary.aov(). Both of these expect an object of class aov as the argument.

aov(data~expgroups)
## Call:
##    aov(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## Terms:
##                 expgroups Residuals
## Sum of Squares  109.44793  10.25103
## Deg. of Freedom         1         8
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.13198
## Estimated effects may be unbalanced

summary(aov(data~expgroups))  # same as `summary.aov()`
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## expgroups    1 109.45  109.45   85.41 1.52e-05 ***
## Residuals    8  10.25    1.28                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

If the ratio \(SSB/SSW = SumSq(expgroups)/SumSq(Residuals)\) is a lot different from 1, we can conclude that there is a difference between the groups. Here, the report tells us that the SSB is ~60, and the SSW ~10, so this looks pretty good.

But to get a proper \(p\)-value, we actually want the F-statistic, which uses the mean sums of squares: \(F = MS_B / MS_W\). To get the mean sums of squares, we also need the degrees of freedom. The between-groups df are [# groups - 1], and the df for the residuals (within groups) are [# data points - # groups]. So here, \(F = (SSB/df.exp) / (SSW/df.res) = (SSB/1) / (SSW/8)\).

ANOVA Method 2: lm()

The lm() function makes a linear model of the data as explained by expgroups. The expgroups factor is the independent variable, and data is the dependent variable.

NOTE: As with the ANOVA summary function, there are two different ways to get a summary of a linear model object produced by the lm() function: summary(linear_model) and summary.lm(linear_model). Both methods expect an object of class lm as the argument.

datalm = lm(data ~ expgroups)

summary(datalm)  # same as `summary.lm()`
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.7019 -0.8204  0.2021  0.7839  1.4979 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   -1.0026     0.5062  -1.980    0.083 .  
## expgroupstrt   6.6166     0.7159   9.242 1.52e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.132 on 8 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9144, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9037 
## F-statistic: 85.41 on 1 and 8 DF,  p-value: 1.524e-05

Using the anova() function on the linear model (object) gives you the same information as the summary of aov():

anova(datalm) # same as summary(aov(data ~ expgroups))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: data
##           Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## expgroups  1 109.448 109.448  85.414 1.524e-05 ***
## Residuals  8  10.251   1.281                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Comparing results of ANOVA and linear modeling

The null hypothesis of linear modeling is that the slope of the line is 0. In contrast, the null hypothesis of the ANOVA is that the variance of all of the data combined is the same as the variance of the individual groups.

In other words, the baseline for lm is the control, whereas for ANOVA there is no baseline; you simply look at all the differences between the groups. Concomitantly, a \(t\)-statistic compares means, whereas an \(F\)-statistic compares variance. For a linear model, the \(t\)-test compares the observed slope vs.Â the expected slope of \(\beta=0\), i.e.Â a horizontal line.

Despite these methodological differences, notice that the \(p\)-values are the same. This is because in both cases, the variance is still needed to make a good estimate of significance. As we saw before, for a model with only one explanatory variable, the \(F\)-statistic is equivalent the square of the \(t\)-statistic. Comparison with each reference distribution gives the same \(p\)-value.

We can compute the \(t\)-statistic and \(p\)-value from the linear model âby handâ using the following:

  • coef(linear_model) â the estimated coefficients for the slope and intercept
  • sqrt(diag(vcov(linear_model)) â the standard errors of the estimated model parameters, which are obtained from the diagonal elements of their covariance matrix
# coefficients
coef(datalm)
##  (Intercept) expgroupstrt 
##    -1.002582     6.616583

# estimated error
sqrt(diag(vcov(datalm)))
##  (Intercept) expgroupstrt 
##    0.5062368    0.7159269

# t-statistics from the linear model
tstats <- coef(datalm) / sqrt(diag(vcov(datalm)))
tstats
##  (Intercept) expgroupstrt 
##    -1.980461     9.241981

# p-value
2 * pt(abs(tstats), df = df.residual(datalm), lower.tail = FALSE)
##  (Intercept) expgroupstrt 
## 8.298950e-02 1.524102e-05

# t-statistic squared is the same as the F-statistic
tstats^2
##  (Intercept) expgroupstrt 
##     3.922225    85.414209

Normally distributed data for three groups

Letâs make another group and call it trt2 with the same sample size, but a different mean. Then, letâs combine this with our previous data and make a new linear model.

# new treatment group
trt2= rnorm(5,mean=10)

# combine data
data = c(ctrl,trt,trt2)
expgroups = factor(rep(c("ctrl", "trt", "trt2"), each=5))

# make a boxplot
boxplot(data ~ expgroups)


# make a new linear model
datalm = lm(data ~ expgroups)
summary(datalm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.7019 -0.7128  0.1424  0.5094  1.4979 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    -1.0026     0.4300  -2.331    0.038 *  
## expgroupstrt    6.6166     0.6082  10.879 1.43e-07 ***
## expgroupstrt2  11.0499     0.6082  18.169 4.27e-10 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.9616 on 12 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9654, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9596 
## F-statistic: 167.2 on 2 and 12 DF,  p-value: 1.728e-09

For this model, âEstimateâ gives the slope of the line between the control and each experimental group. This is around 5 comparing ctl-trt1 and ~10 comparing ctl-trt2. This is just the difference between the means.

We get \(p\)-values for the individual groups, and an overall \(p\)-value for the model.

Letâs compare this to the ANOVA result:

summary(aov(data ~ expgroups))
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## expgroups    2  309.2  154.61   167.2 1.73e-09 ***
## Residuals   12   11.1    0.92                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

This summary tells us that the total variance among groups is a lot bigger than the variance within groups, but we donât get any information about the significance of each group on its own.

Tukeyâs honest significant difference test

We can use âTukeyâs honest significant differenceâ test, TukeyHSD, to help us figure this out. The TukeyHSD shows the magnitude of the differences between all pairwise combinations of the groups, so you can tell which groups are responsible for any major differences between them.

TukeyHSD(aov(data ~ expgroups))
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## $expgroups
##                diff      lwr       upr    p adj
## trt-ctrl   6.616583 4.994038  8.239128 4.00e-07
## trt2-ctrl 11.049946 9.427402 12.672491 0.00e+00
## trt2-trt   4.433363 2.810819  6.055908 2.66e-05

Again, performing the anova() function on the linear model gives us the same results as the summary of aov(). However, we cannot perform TukeyHSD() on the results of the anova() function. (Why is this?)

anova(datalm)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: data
##           Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## expgroups  2 309.225 154.613   167.2 1.728e-09 ***
## Residuals 12  11.097   0.925                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

What if trt2 is the same as trt?


# new dataset with two treatment samples drawn from the same distribution
trt2= rnorm(5,mean=5)
data = c(ctrl,trt,trt2)
expgroups = factor(rep(c("ctrl", "trt","trt2"), each=5))
boxplot(data ~ expgroups)

datalm = lm(data ~ expgroups)
summary(datalm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.7019 -0.8147  0.1968  0.6667  2.1118 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    -1.0026     0.5322  -1.884    0.084 .  
## expgroupstrt    6.6166     0.7526   8.791 1.41e-06 ***
## expgroupstrt2   6.1073     0.7526   8.115 3.25e-06 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.19 on 12 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8886, Adjusted R-squared:   0.87 
## F-statistic: 47.87 on 2 and 12 DF,  p-value: 1.91e-06

Now letâs perform an ANOVA using aov() and run Tukeyâs HSD test.

summary(aov(data~expgroups))
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## expgroups    2 135.56   67.78   47.87 1.91e-06 ***
## Residuals   12  16.99    1.42                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
TukeyHSD(aov(data~expgroups))
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = data ~ expgroups)
## 
## $expgroups
##                 diff       lwr      upr     p adj
## trt-ctrl   6.6165831  4.608708 8.624459 0.0000039
## trt2-ctrl  6.1073228  4.099447 8.115198 0.0000090
## trt2-trt  -0.5092603 -2.517136 1.498615 0.7811364

Notice that for the ANOVA, the differences between the groups are the same as the slopes between the control and the treatment groups in the linear model!
